<DOC><DOCNO> AP880926-0232 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 0956EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-Tateandamp;Lyle     09-26 0214</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Tate andamp; Lyle,0220</SECOND><HEAD>Tate And Lyle To Buy U.S. Sugar Operations</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Tate andamp; Lyle PLC said Monday it has agreed toacquire the sugar refining operations of Amstar Corp. for about$305 million, strengthening the British company's position in theU.S. sweetener market.   At the same time, Tate andamp; Lyle said it will seek a buyer for itsmuch-smaller sugar refining operations in Yonkers, N.Y., held bythe British company's Refined Sugars Inc. subsidiary. Tate and Lylesaid it expects proceeds from this sale to exceed $100 million.   The Amstar sugar business, which markets under the Domino brandname, will be jointly owned by Tate andamp; Lyle and Redpath IndustriesLtd. through Refined Sugars Inc.   Redpath is a publicly quoted Canadian concern which is 50.15percent owned by Tate andamp; Lyle. The two companies each own half ofRefined Sugars.   ``This ... gives the Tate andamp; Lyle group a significant position inthe U.S. cane sugar refining industry,'' said Tate andamp; Lyle ChairmanNeil Shaw.   Amstar, which has its headquarters in Stamford, Conn., has sugarrefineries in Brooklyn, N.Y., Baltimore and New Orleans.   Tate andamp; Lyle acquired U.S.-based Staley Continental, a leadingproducer of corn sweeteners, in June. In 1985, it formed WesternSugar Co. in the United States.</TEXT></DOC>